Narrative:
On May [XXX], 2025 at 8:00 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV came to a stop facing westbound on [XXX] at a stop sign at the intersection at [XXX] in a location where vegetation to the left of the AV created occlusion of the approaching near-side sidewalk. After coming to a stop at the stop line, the Waymo AV began moving forward into the intersection at [XXX] when a cyclist that had been traveling northwest on the near-side sidewalk along [XXX] entered the crosswalk and the front tire of the bike made contact with the front driver side of the Waymo AV. The cyclist fell to the ground.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The cyclist later informed Waymo of a minor injury.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX] in San Francisco. At that time, a cyclist on an eBike came to a stop in the bike lane to the right of the Zoox vehicle. The cyclist began to proceed before the light turned green and headed straight. After the light turned green, the Zoox vehicle proceeded straight towards [XXX]. While nearly through the intersection, the cyclist abruptly veered left into the path of the Zoox vehicle and accelerated toward the front of the Zoox vehicle in violation of a red crosswalk signal and in violation of the Zoox vehicle's right-of-way. The Zoox vehicle appropriately braked hard in response to the cyclist's maneuver, but contact was unavoidable. The eBike laterally impacted the Zoox vehicle's right front fender and body side, then the cyclist impacted the right front body of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then came to a full stop. The cyclist then rode over to the sidewalk and remained briefly stopped on the sidewalk before getting back on the eBike and riding away. The Zoox vehicle cleared the intersection, then pulled over on [XXX], and shortly after was towed from the scene for inspection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the right front body. The police were not called. No injuries were reported nor apparent with the cyclist.
The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

On February [XXX], 2025 at 12:10 PM PT two Waymo Autonomous Vehicles ("Waymo AVs") operating in San Francisco, CA were involved in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX].
The first Waymo AV was parked at the northwest-bound curb on [XXX]for passenger dropoff. A second Waymo AV (2024 Jaguar I-PACE SADHW2S17R1[XXX], 38,609 miles) was also parked for a separate passenger dropoff, located adjacent to the first Waymo AV with the bicycle lane of northwest-bound [XXX] between the two Waymo AVs. A bicyclist was traveling northwest-bound on [XXX] and approaching the two Waymo AVs from the rear. As the cyclist was passing between the two Waymo AVs, the rear driver side passenger of the first Waymo AV opened the door of the first Waymo AV into the cyclist. The cyclist then fell into the passenger side of the second Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, both Waymo AVs' Level 4 ADS were engaged in autonomous mode. Neither Waymo AV sustained damage. The cyclist was able to move out of the roadway independently and was then transported from the scene in an ambulance. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Cruise submits this updated report to confirm there was no physical contact between the AV and the cyclist and to provide additional details about this incident. On November [XXX], 2024 at 7:23PM CST, a Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV") operating in supervised autonomous mode in Houston, Texas was traveling west on [XXX] when it decelerated as it approached a speed bump. As the AV began to slowly traverse the speed bump, it maneuvered slightly left to provide room for a cyclist approaching from behind the AV on the right-hand side. As the cyclist approached quickly from behind the AV, they moved from the right side of the road to the left side and attempted to maneuver around the AV, between the AV and a parked vehicle. The cyclist then lost control of their bike while maneuvering the speed bump and fell to the ground in front of and to the left of the AV. The AV came to a complete stop and the Cruise safety driver took manual control of the AV, remaining stationary. The cyclist proceeded to get to their feet and spoke with the safety driver, but did not report any injuries when asked. There was no indication of property damage to the AV.

On November [XXX], 2024 at 7:23PM CST, a Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV) operating in supervised autonomous mode in Houston, Texas was traveling west on [XXX] when it decelerated as it approached a speed bump. As the AV began to slowly traverse the speed bump, it maneuvered slightly left. A cyclist approached quickly from behind the AV and attempted to maneuver around the AV on the left-hand side between the AV and a parked vehicle. Based on the initial review, the cyclist then lost control of their bike while riding over the speed bump and fell to the ground in front of and to the left of the AV. The AV came to a complete stop and the Cruise safety driver took manual control of the AV, remaining stationary. Cruise has not confirmed that there was any physical contact between the AV and the cyclist. The cyclist proceeded to get to their feet and spoke with the safety driver, but did not report any injuries when asked. There was no indication of property damage to the AV.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), was completing a mission traveling southwest on [XXX] in San Francisco. As the vehicle was completing its mission and slowed to a near stop, the Zoox vehicle operator identified an oncoming bicycle, disengaged from autonomy, and braked the Zoox vehicle to a full stop in its lane. The bicyclist crossed into the oncoming traffic lane occupied by the Zoox vehicle and continued rapidly while steering directly towards the front of the Zoox vehicle. The bicycle made contact with the front bumper of the stationary Zoox vehicle and the bicyclist made contact with the hood of the Zoox vehicle and fell to the ground. The police and emergency responders arrived at the scene and the bicyclist was transported to a hospital. The police report describes injuries to the bicyclist as "loss of consciousness, complaint of pain to back, knee, and toe nail". This 10-Day update provides complete information to date for this incident.

After contact, the bicyclist appeared uninjured, got up and left the scene on the bicycle.

On July [xxx], 2024, at 12:59 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in [XXX], California was involved in an alleged collision with a non-motorist (cyclist) at a parking garage exit on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was exiting a parking garage onto [XXX], between [XXX] and [XXX]. As the Waymo AV approached the garage exit, it stopped for a cyclist who was approaching from the left. The Waymo AV remained stationary as the cyclist passed in front of the vehicle, slowed, and appeared to begin to dismount. The cyclist then reached out a hand and made contact with the front passenger side of the stationary Waymo AV, backed the bicycle up slightly, dropped the bicycle, then fell to the ground. 
At the time of the possible impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present. The cyclist received medical attention at the scene and was reportedly transported to a hospital by local emergency services. The Waymo AV did not sustain any damage. 
Even though this event may involve intentional contact by the bicyclist with a stationary Waymo AV and the occurrence of actual impact between the Waymo AV and the cycle is not clear, Waymo is reporting this event as a crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a media report included an allegation of a crash and because a vulnerable road user (cyclist) influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and reportedly was transported to a hospital for medical treatment as a result of the event. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On February [XXX], 2024 at 2:34 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a bicyclist on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] and came to a stop at a 4-way stop sign intersection at [XXX]. When it was the Waymo AVs turn at the intersection, the Waymo AV entered the intersection to proceed straight. At this point, a delivery truck traveling eastbound on [XXX] was already in the middle of the intersection (the delivery truck arrived at its stop sign first and proceeded into the intersection before the Waymo AV). As the Waymo AV passed the rear of the delivery truck, an occluded bicyclist who was traveling behind the delivery truck became visible and was making a sharp left turn onto northbound [XXX], in front of the Waymo AVs path. The cyclist had entered the 4-way stop intersection without stopping or yielding. The Waymo AV detected the bicyclist, applied heavy braking, but was unable to avoid contact with the bicyclist before coming to a full stop. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained minor body damage, and the bicyclist reported minor injuries and damage to their bicycle. Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

As reported by Argo AI to Ford on September [XXX], 2022 (Report # 30290-3913-1), an Argo AI Autonomous Vehicle ("Argo AV") was impacted by a cyclist while traveling east on [XXX] and approaching [XXX]. The Argo AV was traveling in its lane adjacent to a cyclist who was traveling in a marked bike lane. On February [XXX], 2022 at 5:46 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a bicyclist on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and traveling southbound on [XXX] when it came to a stop at [XXX]. As the Waymo AV proceeded, a bicyclist traveling northbound on [XXX] proceeded through the stop sign without stopping in order to make a left turn onto westbound [XXX]. The Waymo AV began to brake and the test driver (in the driver's seating position), disengaged the AV system and continued braking. As the bicyclist attempted to complete their left turn, the bicyclist made contact with the driver side rear corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date.

This report is an update to 30412-1138. A Cruise autonomous vehicle (Cruise AV), operating in autonomous mode, was traveling southbound on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. The Cruise AV was traveling 24.4 mph upon entering the intersection with [XXX] on a green light. As the Cruise AV continued through the intersection, a bicyclist traveling eastbound on [XXX] failed to stop for their red light and entered the intersection. The Cruise AV was disengaged from autonomous mode and the Cruise AV operator braked to a speed of 8.7 mph and, shortly thereafter, the bicyclist made contact with the Cruise AV, damaging the front of the Cruise AV and the bicycle. The cyclist verbally reported they were okay. However, the Cruise AV Operator noticed minor injuries to the cyclist. Police and Emergency Medical Services were called, but the cyclist left the scene before the police or EMS arrived. [REDACTED CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

On August [XXX], 2021 at approximately 4:48pm, Waymo Autonomous Vehicle operated by a Transdev employee, in the city of San Francisco, California was stuck by a bicycle at [XXX] and [XXX]. The Waymo AV had stopped at the stop sign on [XXX] and, when the intersection was clear, began to proceed westbound through the intersection with [XXX]. At the approximately the same time, a cyclist traveling northbound ran the stop sign on [XXX], began to turn right into [XXX] but immediately veered left to continue northbound across the crosswalk on [XXX], where it stuck the rear drivers side of the Waymo AV. The cyclist stated upright and immediately rode away, continuing northbound on [XXX]. The Bicyclist caused a minor scratches and marks on the rear divers side bumper of the Waymo AV. The Waymo AV was operating with a driver (in the driver's seating position), who transitioned the vehicle from autonomous to manual mode approximately 1 second before the impact occurred. At the time of impact, the Waymo AV was in manual mode. Trasndev Alternative Services (TAS) is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of the Standing General Order 2021-01 because of a vulnerable road user was involved. Transdev may supplement or correct it's reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report is a duplicate to Waymo LLC's report WaymoLLC-202108[XXX]-0 (rev. 202108[XXX]200020).
